question:
District category contains Restaurant District, Government Complex, and Institute District.
Supermarkets category contains King Soopers, Stop & Shop, and Lidl.
Product category contains Canned Sauces, Canned Peas, and Bagels.
Ingredient category contains Hot Sauce, Molasses, and Ginger.
The number of each Stop & Shop 's Bagels equals 12 times the sum of each Stop & Shop 's Canned Peas, each Bagels 's Molasses, and each King Soopers 's Canned Peas.
The number of each Canned Sauces 's Ginger equals each Government Complex 's Product.
The number of each Lidl 's Canned Peas equals each Restaurant District 's King Soopers.
The number of each King Soopers 's Canned Peas equals 6.
The number of each Lidl 's Bagels equals 10 more than the difference of each King Soopers 's Canned Peas and each Lidl 's Canned Peas.
The number of each Stop & Shop 's Canned Peas equals 14.
The number of each Bagels 's Molasses equals 12 more than each Stop & Shop 's Canned Peas.
The number of each Canned Peas 's Hot Sauce equals each Stop & Shop 's Product.
The number of each Government Complex 's Stop & Shop equals each Lidl 's Canned Peas.
The number of each Restaurant District 's King Soopers equals 3.
The number of each Institute District 's King Soopers equals 10 times the difference of each Bagels 's Molasses and each Stop & Shop 's Canned Peas.
How many Supermarkets does Restaurant District have?
solution:
Define each Restaurant District 's King Soopers as U; So U = 3.
Define each Restaurant District 's Supermarkets as J; So J = U = 3.
